## **WELCOME TO OMNIHAMMER**

Warhammer 40,000, from 3rd edition through 7th edition, shared a common core rule set that endured for nearly 20-years from the release of 3rd edition in 1998 until 8th edition in 2017\. For many players, this era represents the “classic” 40K experience, and for one reason or another \- whether it be the lore, the gameplay, or the aesthetics \- remains a version of the game still worth playing.  Many people playing today started after the beginning of 8th edition and missed out on the era of customization and dramatic gameplay in the classic era.  Such players who feel that the \#New40K era of rulesets feels bland or dumbed down may find that OmniHammer is the correct edition for them.

**OmniHammer** is a fork of **ProHammer Classic**. The aim is to tighten up the simulationist aspects, do away with some of the gamified rules implemented in the name of speed rolling, and make the game feel more like a *war* game than a war *game*.  This is not claimed to be a better version of OmniHammer, just a different version for those who may not agree with some of the design decisions of the original.  OmniHammer takes an “everyone is here” style approach, which seeks to include rules to allow models from any codex, past or present, to fight alongside each other on the grimdark battlefields of the 41st millennium.  Community feedback is encouraged and desired.  If you play OmniHammer, please let us know what felt good, what felt bad, and what needs clarification.  It’s easy to get tunnel vision and having different sets of eyes on a project like this can only improve it.  We encourage the use of the Google Docs comment feature.

